body: Ort::Session::Run threw an C/C++ exception.  Could you please catch the exception and print out the error message?
Please share the ONNX format model, the device log (Android logcat) around the time of crash, and the full crash call-stack

You model has some very large steps (1000000000 which is very close to 2^30) for Slice op in one or more subgraphs, this will cause integer overflow on 32bit system (not only arm32, this will repro on x86 also),
There will be a fix in ONNX Runtime, but to work around you may try to use a smaller step in the Slice op

issue.title: Fix integer overflow for large step for Slice OP

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: Fix integer overflow for large step for Slice OP

**Motivation and Context**
- The crash in #9368, is caused by the model contains very large step for Slice op, the step is 1000000000 which is close to 2^30, the will cause SafeInt overflow at https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/74eaaad768e0a5ad5e65b818605383c73dece509/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/utils.h#L161, the variable `pitch` is `ptrdiff_t` which is platform specific, and the behavior after this integer overflow is undefined, in theory, if a large enough step is given, this will also repro on 64 bit system
- The fix is to clamp the step between [-dim, dim] for the corresponding dimension, since any steps over it will simply push over the boundary
- Switch to std::clamp for Slice and some minor code update

rename.from: Crash with sigbus: illegal alignment on Android  arm-v7a when session run
rename.to: Crash with sigbus: illegal alignment on 32bit system when session run

body:
Even running on the same hardware, the ORT compile with `armeabi-v7a` and `arm64-v8a` are using 2 different instruction sets, `arm64-v8a` can take advantage of the new 64bit hardware and `armeabi-v7a` cannot. And since the arm32 is being gradually phased out, our platform specific optimization is mainly focusing on arm64. The performance difference is expected.

Please close this issue if it is resolved.
